result.execSummary:
The defendant Breyon Montrell Parker was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Retail Theft - Intentionally Take >$500 - $5000) [Modifiers: PTAC, as a Party to a Crime], a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.50(1m)(b).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Breyon Montrell Parker in court with attorney Avery L Goodrich.  Sarah McNutt appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

Sentencing proceeds.  Statements made by the state, defense counsel and defendant. 

AS TO COUNT 1:    Defendant sentenced to serve 1 YEAR at the HOUSE OF CORRECTION, straight time, consecutive to any other sentence defendant is currently serving. 
Credit for ZERO days time served. 

COURT STAYS sentence and placed defendant on PROBATION for a period of 2 years under the supervision of the Wisconsin Department of Corrections.

CONDITIONS OF PROBATION (AS TO COUNT 1):
* Comply with the standard rules of probation.
* SERVE 45 DAYS "condition time" - STAYED.  To be used at the Probation Department's discretion.
* No contact with Ragman clothing store inside Bayshore Mall located at 5800 N. Bayshore Drive, Glendale, WI.
* No contact with the co-actors.
* Complete a job training program to enhance ability to obtain employment.
* Seek and maintain full-time employment.
* Cooperate and participate with an AODA assessment and follow any recommended treatment.
* Maintain absolute sobriety and submit to random urine screens.
* Provide a DNA sample and PAY DNA surcharge - to be paid over a period of probation.  Failure to pay will result in a civil judgment.
* PAY the balance of all applicable court costs, fees, and surcharges - to be paid over a period of probation.  Failure to pay will result in a civil judgment.

OTHER COURT ORDERS:
* Court ordered the Dosage Probation Program.
* Court ordered restitution set at ZERO.
  
Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon he may never possess a firearm or body armor.

Defendant Breyon Montrell Parker in court with attorney Avery L Goodrich.  Sarah McNutt appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

This matter was originally scheduled for a Final Pretrial Conference today, however, the parties have now reached an agreement.

Defense moves to withdraw the motion to suppress.
No objections.
Court GRANTS defense motion and allows the motion to suppress to be "WITHDRAWN".

AS TO COUNT 1:    Defendant changes plea to GUILTY. Defendant examined as to his plea, advised of his Constitutional rights and the maximum penalty. Court found that defendant freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived his rights. Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea. Court found defendant guilty as charged in the information and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record. Defendant is advised he is a convicted felon and may not possess any firearms. Defendant is advised he is unable to vote in any election until civil rights are restored. Defendant further advised that if he is not a US citizen deportation is possible.
